[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426480&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426480&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

I have spent some time on this question for other organizations, and I
can see how you will be reticent to assume authority to ask for the
NASA.GOV domain, though you might ask for AMES.GOV (or AMES.NASA.GOV if
someone else has already registered NASA.GOV).

You can later shift from AMES.GOV to AMES.NASA.GOV while retaining
AMES.GOV as a nickname (thus appearing in two domains, which will
entail some administrative work to assure that the right entries are in
the right tables, everywhere).  I suggest that you register AMES.GOV
now and also prompt NASA to request registration of NASA.GOV (perhaps
with you as the interim administrator).  

The objective is to get going without stepping on toes or stressing the
bureaucracy, and do it in such a way as to only require domain table
changes later, rather than real name changes (as two other folks have
already warned).

One of the main ideas with domains is that the whole network namespace
should be table controlled.  If we name things right, then
reconfiguration can be redone with table changes only.  Sounds nice!

Best - Stef

